   {:e #blake3 "3c3f34f351290727aad51107d8782e055c2854ac9d3145bf1f3aa69424e2e34d" :a :db/ident :v :harvest/session-braid-user-1774394164 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "3c3f34f351290727aad51107d8782e055c2854ac9d3145bf1f3aa69424e2e34d" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-5: NaN propagation in graph.rs and bilateral.rs. The hand-written eigensolver (Jacobi rotation) in query/graph.rs has a hardcoded iteration limit. If the matrix does not converge within that limit, eigenvalues are approximate. No convergence flag is returned — callers cannot distinguish converged from unconverged results. Downstream: Fiedler value lambda_2, Cheeger constant, spectral gap, Renyi entropy spectrum all propagate whatever the eigensolver returns. If eigenvalues contain NaN (from division by zero in normalization, e.g., PageRank on a graph with zero outgoing edges), NaN propagates through: (1) spectral_gap = lambda_2/lambda_max — NaN if lambda_max=0, (2) cheeger constant — involves sqrt of eigenvalue ratios, (3) Phi normalization — entity_count_for_phi could be 0, (4) Ricci curvature — edge-weight ratios. In Rust, NaN comparisons are always false: NaN > x = false, NaN < x = false, NaN == x = false. This means any comparison-based logic (routing score ranking, task priority ordering, boundary threshold checks) silently drops NaN entries or short-circuits to the wrong branch. The 40 unwrap() calls in graph.rs amplify the risk — an unexpected intermediate result could panic. Specific locations: spectral_decomposition_adaptive(), ricci_curvature_adaptive(), ricci_summary(), tx_barcode(). The fix is: (1) is_finite() guards on eigensolver output, (2) convergence flag in eigendecomposition return type, (3) explicit NaN → 0.0 or NaN → None at computation boundaries.; Session entity: :recon/trace-c515876c59d19ee7; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-10: Datalog evaluator has no termination guard or negation guard. query/evaluator.rs (1,786 LOC) implements stratified fixpoint evaluation with naive bottom-up iteration. Two gaps: (1) TERMINATION: Fixpoint iteration terminates because the result set grows monotonically in a finite domain. But transitive closure on a cyclic graph produces unbounded derived tuples — iteration consumes unbounded memory/time. No timeout. No result-set limit. No max-iteration guard. OOM kill is the only termination mechanism. (2) NEGATION: Stage 0 supports strata 0-1 (monotonic only). But there is no guard preventing construction of negated clauses. If a query with negation-as-failure is submitted, behavior is undefined — silently ignored or wrong results. 28 unwrap() calls in evaluator.rs include user-provided input (variable lookups from bindings). A malformed query with an unbound variable triggers a panic. The fix for termination is a max_tuples parameter (default 100_000). The fix for negation is a validation pass that rejects negated clauses with a clear error. The fix for panics is replacing unwrap() with proper error propagation.; Session entity: :task/t-957f56e0; Session entity: :task/t-7c8fdc8f; Session entity: :task/t-8e03ba43; Session entity: :task/t-dac5f985; Session entity: :task/t-274cd1e2; Session entity: :recon/trace-6507a85d533c2c56; Session entity: :task/t-72a60f30; Session entity: :recon/trace-1a3d63b64d17672b; Session entity: :recon/trace-845f4e40495cc4b8; Session entity: :recon/trace-b8a0ac65c2290561; Session entity: :task/t-52527d7b; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-9: C8 substrate independence violation in methodology.rs. The kernel module methodology.rs (1,396 LOC) contains DDIS-specific hardcoded weights: INV/ADR/NEG category detection, spec language pattern matching (contains 'INV-' or 'ADR-'), methodology scoring that assumes the DDIS ontology. The C8 constraint says: 'The braid kernel must not contain logic specific to any programming language, test framework, specification format, or project methodology — including DDIS itself.' Test: 'would this code make sense for a React project with Jest tests and Jira tickets?' Answer: no — methodology.rs looks for INV- and ADR- prefixes that don't exist in Jira. Some guidance.rs functions also have DDIS-specific scoring (lines 2706+: ISP projection weights hardcoded for Intent/Spec/Impl). The fix is: move methodology-specific scoring into policy.rs (which already exists for policy manifest weights). Non-DDIS projects would provide a different policy manifest with different ontology patterns and weights. This is not blocking Phase A but it is a genuine constraint violation that should be addressed.; Session entity: :recon/trace-bd99eab487702239; Session entity: :task/t-5ced1271; Session entity: :recon/trace-e176faa13b9bcb7c; Session entity: :task/t-6add3124; Session entity: :task/t-7714a430; Session entity: :recon/trace-d21f9acee681d056; Session entity: :recon/trace-35ba52e7c2f3ce21; Session entity: :recon/trace-84635124a708d1e1; Session entity: :recon/trace-92455084c8f5e42d; Session entity: :recon/trace-930d09ca9f9de810; Session entity: :recon/trace-8559ee36abac614b; Session entity: :recon/trace-25eda8943021949c; Session entity: :recon/trace-c0f812c2690b24d7; Session entity: :recon/trace-264f904b45f09869; Session entity: :recon/trace-e245173eedc29bba; Session entity: :task/t-23cd86e9; Session entity: :task/t-31f6c8b8; Session entity: :recon/trace-39e241cf6b3ca4a7; Session entity: :task/t-28e0b1aa; Session entity: :recon/trace-796d167bb6f44c59; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-7: F(S) monotonicity claim is false in practice. bilateral.rs module doc (line 15) claims 'F(S(t+1)) >= F(S(t)) (Monotonic convergence — Law L1)' — stated as a mathematical theorem. But Session 033 documents a drop from F(S)=0.67 to F(S)=0.58 due to 'Views H=0.5 placeholder vs batch methodology_score'. If F(S) can decrease during normal operation, the convergence guarantee is void. The claimed Lyapunov property requires ALL store operations to be monotonic wrt F(S), which is not true: (1) Adding a low-quality observation decreases the coverage ratio (covered/total increases total without increasing covered). (2) Adding a spec element without an implementation link decreases the coverage component. (3) The spec_count counter in MaterializedViews includes retracted specs (LEDGER-2), so the denominator grows even when specs are removed. The module doc language should be downgraded from 'Lyapunov function satisfying F(S(t+1)) >= F(S(t))' to 'heuristic convergence metric that generally increases as coherence improves but is not formally monotonic'. The spectral certificate and convergence rate bound (mixing time O(log(n)/g)) depend on this property and are therefore also aspirational, not guaranteed.; Session entity: :task/t-d47fc7f6; Session entity: :recon/trace-d734631d61359d31; Session entity: :recon/trace-4b54d94480d44df4; Session entity: :task/t-49a8f2d5; Session entity: :recon/trace-7c82c41272e1a623; Session entity: :task/t-4090d274; Session entity: :recon/trace-2ef9ab02148b64fb; Session entity: :recon/trace-3de0bba30daff3cf; Session entity: :task/t-268591ca; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-3: LIVE view ignores bare retractions — silent stale data. Both from_datoms() (store.rs:1052) and apply_datoms() (store.rs:1124) guard LIVE view updates with 'if d.op == Op::Assert'. A Retract datom is inserted into the BTreeSet and all secondary indexes, but the live_view BTreeMap<(EntityId, Attribute), (Value, TxId)> is NEVER updated for retractions. Consequence: if entity E has attribute A asserted with value V1 at tx T1, live_view[(E,A)] = (V1, T1). If a later tx T2 retracts (E, A, V1), live_view STILL shows (V1, T1). The retracted value remains visible to all live_view consumers. This is safe ONLY because the braid protocol uses retract-then-assert (ADR-COHERENCE-001) — every retraction is paired with a new assertion in the same transaction. But the invariant is NOWHERE ENFORCED. If any code path issues a bare retraction without a paired assert (e.g., task deletion, observation cleanup, external merge), the LIVE view silently shows a ghost value. No grep for 'Retract.*live_view' finds any handling. No test covers 'retract without re-assert on live_view'. The fix is a debug_assert in apply_datoms that flags bare retractions, turning a silent-corruption path into a loud one.; Session entity: :recon/trace-b6ff1ea6bfc0cd1f; Session entity: :task/t-97f40f05; Session entity: :task/t-142a7210; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-8: Kani proofs operate on BTreeSet<Datom>, not full Store. kani_proofs.rs:45 acknowledges: 'Since Kani cannot handle the full Store::genesis() (which involves BLAKE3 hashing, schema construction, and BTreeSet operations), several harnesses operate on the underlying BTreeSet<Datom> directly.' The proofs verify: append-only on BTreeSet, commutativity/associativity/idempotency on BTreeSet union, LWW commutativity on ConflictSet, schema genesis determinism on Schema type. What is NOT verified: secondary index consistency (entity_index, attribute_index, vaet_index, avet_index are maintained by hand in two separate code paths — from_datoms and apply_datoms). LIVE view correctness (LWW resolution via live_view BTreeMap — proved on ConflictSet but not on the live_view code path). MaterializedViews accumulator correctness (observe_datom has no formal model). Schema validation under evolution (adding/removing attributes to a running store). Frontier monotonicity under concurrent operations. The gap is architectural: the proven layer (BTreeSet algebra) is sound, but the unproven layer (indexes, LIVE view, views) is where all the actual queries run. The informal argument 'Store::merge() delegates to BTreeSet::insert()' is true for the datom set but says nothing about the 5 secondary data structures rebuilt in merge().; Session entity: :recon/trace-c6b96e7bcf5783da; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-4: Lattice resolution falls back to LWW silently. resolution.rs line ~158: ResolutionMode::Lattice { lattice_id } is declared in the schema but the lattice join is never computed — the code does '// Stage 0: fall back to LWW'. No warning is emitted. No datom records the fallback. No test verifies that lattice mode produces correct results (because it cannot — it produces LWW results). The Kani proof prove_lattice_join_associativity exists but proves the trivial LWW fallback, not a real lattice join — it is vacuously true. A user who configures ResolutionMode::Lattice for an attribute gets LWW without knowing it. Two agents making semantically-different assertions get the temporally-latest value, not the lattice lub. The schema is lying about the semantics it provides. The minimum fix is a warning datom when lattice mode is requested but not available, or a resolution receipt that records which mode was actually used vs which mode was configured.; Session entity: :recon/trace-5d0b646385ad62cc; Session entity: :recon/trace-dc1257facf60ca4a; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-2: MaterializedViews fitness isomorphism is untested. The views.fitness() method (store.rs:709) claims isomorphism with compute_fitness() in bilateral.rs — the doc says 'Isomorphism invariant: this must match compute_fitness() for the same store state.' But NO test verifies this claim. The two implementations compute the same 7-component F(S) from different data sources: views.fitness() uses incrementally-accumulated counters (observe_datom one-pass), while compute_fitness() does batch computation over the full store. Three specific divergence paths exist: (1) observe_datom ignores Retract ops entirely (line 612), so spec_count, task counters, confidence_sum all include retracted datoms while batch does not. (2) The verification-depth accumulator (lines 634-643) is a no-op — depth is extracted but never stored or used, while batch computation resolves the cross-reference. (3) The task_open/task_in_progress/task_closed counters are monotonically increasing (lines 690-706), acknowledged in a comment as 'approximate — CE-4 will wire callers to use the exact computation path'. These divergences mean guidance routing uses the fast (possibly wrong) F(S) while bilateral reports use the slow (correct) F(S). The user could see F(S)=0.62 in status but F(S)=0.45 in bilateral — inconsistent numbers erode trust.; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-6: No crash-recovery test. LiveStore (live_store.rs, 1028 LOC) claims crash safety via append-only EDN transaction files with fsync. The architecture is: (1) write_tx() writes EDN to txns/ directory with fsync, then applies datoms in-memory. (2) flush() serializes store.bin. (3) On next open, recovery replays all txn files not already reflected in store.bin. This design is sound, but it has NEVER been tested. No test simulates: kill process mid-write, verify recovered store equals pre-crash state. No test verifies: corrupt txn file is handled gracefully (partial write). No test verifies: store.bin + txn files produces the same store as txn files alone (the store.bin is an optimization, not the source of truth). Additionally, the multi-writer race on store.bin is untested: two processes open same .braid, both write txn files, second flush overwrites first's store.bin. Txn files are preserved (no data loss) but store.bin is inconsistent. Next open replays txn files, but if replay logic has a bug, stores diverge silently. The fix is: (1) crash-recovery test: write N txns, delete store.bin, reopen, verify store.datoms() == original. (2) partial-write test: write corrupt bytes to a txn file, verify graceful error handling. (3) multi-writer test: interleave two LiveStore instances on same directory.; Session entity: :task/t-de4045f6; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-1: Four guidance tests are currently failing (1434 pass, 4 fail). The failing tests are: mt_session_scoped_recent_activity, mt_session_scoped_not_penalized_by_old_data, spec_language_turns_counts_observation_with_adr_ref, spec_language_turns_counts_task_with_inv_ref. All four are in guidance.rs and test the M(t) session-scoping logic. The failure modes are assertion failures on expected vs actual counts for spec_language_turns and session-scoped methodology scoring. This means the M(t) subsystem — which CE-MT is about to modify — has a broken foundation. Building CE-MT on top of broken M(t) session scoping guarantees a worse outcome. The test suite being RED is itself an unsoundness: no other test result can be trusted when known regressions exist because the failures may mask interactions. Root cause is likely a recent change to telemetry_from_store() in methodology.rs that changed how session-scoped observations are counted.; Session entity: :recon/trace-dcff8623af88055a; Session entity: :task/t-4e574001; Session entity: :task/t-dc4f7648; UNSOUNDNESS-LEDGER-12: Schema migration has no backward-incompatible change guard. schema.rs (4,864 LOC) supports schema evolution via transaction — adding new attributes to a running store. But there is no guard for backward-incompatible changes: (1) Changing an attribute's value type (e.g., Long to String) after data exists. Existing datoms now violate the schema. (2) Changing cardinality from Many to One. Existing multi-valued datoms are invalid. (3) Changing resolution mode from Multi to LWW. Existing multi-valued conflicts are not resolved. The schema is rebuilt from datoms (Schema::from_datoms), so the LATEST schema assertion wins via LWW. But the existing datoms that were valid under the old schema are not retroactively validated or migrated. The fix is: schema_validate_datoms(store, schema) that checks ALL datoms against the current schema, not just new ones. Run this after any schema-affecting transaction. Report violations as CoherenceViolation. This is Stage 1 work but the gap should be tracked.; Session entity: :recon/trace-456ad636638b12f7; Session entity: :recon/trace-a2b0b38e68912289\nSession entity: :task/t-ec3e8840" :op :assert}
